Kernel Roadmap: microgpt
========================

Goal: implement all compute kernels needed for Karpathy's microgpt, then wire
them into a working tiny transformer that trains on character-level names data.

All kernels use auto-vectorization only (let LLVM emit SIMD). No hand-written
NEON intrinsics -- auto-vec consistently beats NEON by 20-35% because LLVM's
optimizer sees more context and schedules instructions better than we can by hand.

References:
  Blog post:    https://karpathy.github.io/2026/02/12/microgpt/
  Source code:  https://gist.githubusercontent.com/karpathy/8627fe009c40f57531cb18360106ce95/raw/14fb038816c7aae0bb9342c2dbf1a51dd134a5ff/microgpt.py

microgpt architecture:
  - 1 transformer layer, 16-dim embeddings, 4 attention heads, 4-dim per head
  - 16-token context window, vocab size 27 (26 chars + BOS)
  - ~4,192 parameters total
  - RMSNorm (not LayerNorm), ReLU (not GELU), no biases
  - Scalar autograd with topological-sort backward pass
  - Adam optimizer with linear LR decay
  - Trains 1000 steps on character names, then generates samples


Already Done (Forward Compute Kernels)
--------------------------------------

All individual forward kernels for microgpt are implemented.
All have auto-vectorized versions and explicit NEON intrinsic variants (*_neon.py).

[x] embedding      -- row copy from lookup table (wte[token_id], wpe[pos_id])
[x] elementwise add-- z[i] = x[i] + y[i] (tok_emb + pos_emb, residual connections)
[x] rmsnorm        -- sum-of-squares + scaling (split into sumsq + scale kernels)
[x] matvec         -- y[j] = sum_i(W[j][i] * x[i]) (linear projections: Wq/Wk/Wv/Wo/fc1/fc2/lm_head)
[x] dot product    -- score = sum_j(q[j] * k[j]) / sqrt(d) (attention logit computation)
[x] softmax        -- exp(x - max) / sum(exp(x - max)) (attention weights + output probs)
[x] weighted sum   -- out[j] = sum_t(weights[t] * V[t,j]) (attention output aggregation)
[x] relu           -- y[i] = max(0, x[i]) (MLP activation)
[x] cross-entropy  -- loss = -log(softmax(logits)[target]) (fused max + sum-exp)
[x] adam optimizer -- parameter update fusing m, v, m_hat, v_hat, param updates
[x] saxpy          -- y[i] += a * x[i] (general utility)
[x] matmul         -- C = A @ B (tiled, cache-optimized — not directly used in microgpt but available)


Missing — backward pass kernels
-------------------------------

microgpt.py uses scalar autograd (Value.backward()). To replace that with
vectorized kernels, we need backward variants for every differentiable op.

These are listed in the order they'd execute during backpropagation (loss → inputs):

[ ] 1. cross_entropy_backward
     dlogits[i] = softmax[i] - 1{i == target}
     Softmax gradient fused with log-loss derivative. Single vector op.

[ ] 2. linear_backward — two parts:
     dx = dout @ W^T   (transposed matvec — needs new "matvec_t" kernel, see utilities below)
     dW = outer(dout, x)   (rank-1 outer product — no kernel exists)
     Called for every linear() in the model: lm_head, Wo, fc2, fc1, Wv, Wk, Wq.

[ ] 3. relu_backward
     dx = dout * (x > 0)
     Masked passthrough. Trivial — select or multiply by 0/1 mask.

[ ] 4. rmsnorm_backward
     Backward through RMS normalization. Involves recomputing the scale factor
     and a dot-product reduction: dx = (dout - x * dot(dout, x) / sumsq) * scale

[ ] 5. add_backward
     dx = dout, dresidual = dout
     Gradient just copies to both inputs. Trivial (memcpy or no-op if aliased).

[ ] 6. softmax_backward
     dx_i = softmax_i * (dout_i - sum(dout * softmax))
     Needed for attention weight gradients.

[ ] 7. attention_backward
     Backward through dot-product attention: Q·K^T scaling, softmax, V weighting.
     Can be composed from softmax_backward + linear_backward primitives, or fused.

[ ] 8. embedding_backward
     scatter-add: dW_emb[token_id] += dout
     Gradient accumulation into specific embedding rows (wte and wpe).


Missing — forward utilities
----------------------------

[ ] scalar_mul (vector scaling)
     out[i] = x[i] * scalar
     Needed for: logits / temperature (inference), 1/sqrt(head_dim) scaling,
     loss averaging (1/n * sum(losses)).
     Trivial — variant of saxpy with y=0, or standalone kernel.

[ ] matvec_t (transposed matrix-vector multiply)
     y[j] = sum_i(W[i][j] * x[i])   i.e.  y = W^T @ x
     Current matvec.py only does y = W @ x. Transposed variant needed for:
     - Backward pass: dx = dout @ W^T in every linear_backward
     - Could also be used in forward to avoid transposing weight matrices

[ ] outer (rank-1 outer product)
     dW[i][j] = a[i] * b[j]   (or +=)
     Needed for dW = outer(dout, x) in linear_backward.
     Not a standard forward kernel, but essential for training.


Missing — wiring (microgpt.py integration)
-------------------------------------------

[ ] gpt() forward function
     Wire all forward kernels into the transformer forward pass:
     embedding → add → rmsnorm → [attn block → residual add → MLP block → residual add] → linear
     Manage KV cache (append keys/values per position).
     Handle multi-head attention: slice Q/K/V by head, run dot/softmax/weighted_sum per head, concat.

[ ] Training loop
     For each step:
       - Tokenize document
       - Run gpt() forward for each position (autoregressive)
       - Compute cross-entropy loss
       - Run backward pass through all kernels
       - Run Adam optimizer update
       - Zero gradients
     Linear LR decay: lr_t = lr * (1 - step/num_steps)

[ ] Inference loop
     - Run gpt() forward
     - Apply temperature scaling (scalar_mul on logits)
     - Softmax to get probs
     - Sample from distribution (random.choices in Python)
     - Repeat until BOS or max length
